"Huijbregts M.A.J., Gilijamse W., Ragas A.M.J., Reijnders L.","Evaluating uncertainty in environmental life-cycle assessment. A case study comparing two insulation options for a Dutch one-family dwelling",2003,"Environmental Science and Technology","37","11",,"2600","2608",,,10.1021/es020971+,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0037675020&partnerID=40&md5=1e6456281d7e12c4eb5718c87913155f","Department of Environmental Studies, University of Nijmegen, P.O. Box 9010, NL-6500 GL Nijmegen, Netherlands; Inst. for Biodiv./Ecosystem Dynamics, University of Amsterdam, Nieuwe Achtergracht 166, NL-1018 WV, Amsterdam, Netherlands; Netherlands Energy Res. Found. ECN, P.O. Box 1, NL-1755 ZG, Petten, Netherlands","Huijbregts, M.A.J., Department of Environmental Studies, University of Nijmegen, P.O. Box 9010, NL-6500 GL Nijmegen, Netherlands; Gilijamse, W., Netherlands Energy Res. Found. ECN, P.O. Box 1, NL-1755 ZG, Petten, Netherlands; Ragas, A.M.J., Department of Environmental Studies, University of Nijmegen, P.O. Box 9010, NL-6500 GL Nijmegen, Netherlands; Reijnders, L., Inst. for Biodiv./Ecosystem Dynamics, University of Amsterdam, Nieuwe Achtergracht 166, NL-1018 WV, Amsterdam, Netherlands","The evaluation of uncertainty is relatively new in environmental life-cycle assessment (LCA). It provides useful information to assess the reliability of LCA-based decisions and to guide future research toward reducing uncertainty. Most uncertainty studies in LCA quantify only one type of uncertainty, i.e., uncertainty due to input data (parameter uncertainty). However, LCA outcomes can also be uncertain due to normative choices (scenario uncertainty) and the mathematical models involved (model uncertainty). The present paper outlines a new methodology that quantifies parameter, scenario, and model uncertainty simultaneously in environmental life-cycle assessment. The procedure is illustrated in a case study that compares two insulation options for a Dutch one-family dwelling. Parameter uncertainty was quantified by means of Monte Carlo simulation. Scenario and model uncertainty were quantified by resampling different decision scenarios and model formulations, respectively. Although scenario and model uncertainty were not quantified comprehensively, the results indicate that both types of uncertainty influence the case study outcomes. This stresses the importance of quantifying parameter, scenario, and model uncertainty simultaneously. The two insulation options studied were found to have significantly different impact scores for global warming, stratospheric ozone depletion, and eutrophication. The thickest insulation option has the lowest impact on global warming and eutrophication, and the highest impact on stratospheric ozone depletion.",,"Computer simulation; Global warming; Life cycle; Monte Carlo methods; Ozone; Research; Environmental life-cycle assessment; Environmental engineering; cement; concrete; natural gas; polystyrene; household energy; insulation; life cycle analysis; acidification; article; case study; clay; comparative study; decision making; ecotoxicity; environment; eutrophication; evaluation; family; greenhouse effect; heating; home; human; insulation; life cycle; mathematical model; Monte Carlo method; Netherlands; ozone layer; parameter; quantitative analysis; recycling; reliability; scoring system; statistical significance; stratosphere; technique; wood; Air Pollution, Indoor; Housing; Humans; Models, Theoretical; Monte Carlo Method; Reproducibility of Results; Risk Assessment; Netherlands",,"natural gas, 8006-14-2; polystyrene, 9003-53-6",,,,"Consoli, F., Allen, D., Boustead, I., Fava, J., Franklin, W., Jensen, A.A., De Oude, N., Vigon, B., (1993) Guidelines for Life-Cycle Assessment: A 'Code of Practice', , Society of Environmental Toxicology and Chemistry: Pensacola, FL; Heijungs, R., (1994) Ecol. Econ., 10, pp. 69-81; Hendrickson, C., Horvath, A., Joshi, S., Lave, L., (1998) Environ. Sci. Technol., 32, pp.